The governorship candidate of the Action Democratic Congress (ADC) in the June 18 election in Ekiti State, Dr. Oluwole Oluyede, yesterday said he had no plan to step down for any candidate. He said he was still in the race to succeed Governor Kayode Fayemi, adding that being a serious-minded person, “I don’t change my mind when I set on achieving a purpose.”   AbdulRazaq swears in seven perm secs     APC stakeholders endorse Fayemi’s ex-commissioner for Senate     Tech-U honours outgoing VC with symposium   Oluyede, featuring on a local radio programme aired on Cruise FM, described the insinuations that he had withdrawn from the race as untrue and baseless. He said there was no plan by him to step down for any contestant, adding that his desire to rescue Ekiti people remained the driving force behind his ambition. Oluyede said the mandate he was pursuing was germane to the growth and development of the state, noting that his aspiration to govern Ekiti State did not start in a day and could not be quenched.